from pons and crosses in cerebellopontine angle","Exits ventrally from midbrain without decussation","Exits ventrally from midbrain and crosses in the interpeduncular fossa","Exits laterally from pons without decussation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrochlear nerve exits dorsally from the midbrain and decussates in the superior medullary velum\u003C/strong\u003E. This makes it unique among cranial nerves as the only one that exits from the dorsal aspect of the brainstem. After decussation, it wraps around the midbrain to enter the orbit where it innervates the superior oblique muscle of the contralateral eye.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExits dorsally from pons and crosses in cerebellopontine angle\u003C/strong\u003E describes an incorrect anatomical location as the nerve emerges from midbrain, not pons, and crosses in the superior medullary velum. \u003Cstrong\u003EExits ventrally from midbrain without decussation\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eexits ventrally from midbrain and crosses in the interpeduncular fossa\u003C/strong\u003E both incorrectly describe ventral emergence when the nerve uniquely exits dorsally, and the latter incorrectly identifies the crossing location. \u003Cstrong\u003EExits laterally from pons without decussation\u003C/strong\u003E incorrectly places the emergence site at the pons rather than midbrain and fails to account for the essential decussation that occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis unique anatomical arrangement means that each trochlear nerve nucleus controls the superior oblique muscle of the opposite eye.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The trochlear nerve is unique as the only cranial nerve that exits the brainstem dorsally.","The trochlear nerve decussates in the superior medullary velum before exiting the brainstem.","The trochlear nerve innervates only the superior oblique muscle of the contralateral eye."],"references":["Kim SY, Motlagh M, Naqvi IA. Neuroanatomy, Cranial Nerve 4 (Trochlear) [Updated 2023 Jul 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537244/","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98543"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16280"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98543","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98543"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-29T19:43:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-29T19:45:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8971"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116550"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interp